column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While on the dock, one wet carton containing one, one liter plastic bottle was discovered.  Approximately, one-quarter liter of free product was released and absorbed by the carton.  Apparently, the release was due to the carton being dropped during handling.  BAX Global personnel placed the wet carton and leaking container into one, ten gallon poly recovery drum which will be held at the facility pending disposition.  The remainder of the shipment will be forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the result of being dropped during handling, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: Lack of blocking and bracing resulted in a plastic drum falling over during transit while out for city delivery. The driver was making a delivery to a customer of freight other than this hazmat freight. The hazmat freight had a totally separate consignee than where this spill occurred. The driver no  ticed the trailer leaking. The Safety and Security Department was contacted, we immediately contracted a clean up team to respond to the spill. The spill was properly cleaned and the waste placed into a proper overpack container. Supplemental report for accurate costs. Costs include response to the   original spill, transfer of product into a new drum and waste disposal.
column169: Proper blocking and bracing would have prevented this spill.

column168: No 202 was proceeding north on the Millinocket Subdivision with two locomotives, 9 loads and 11 empties.  At Mile 46.88, approximately 18 miles into their trip, the 16th car in the train, GATX 19088 Diesel Fuel, experienced a burned off journal on the 2nd wheel set on the north end of the car.  At Mile 48.70 the burnt off journal wheel set kinked out from under the car allowing the side frame to drop.  When the side frames shifted, the remaining wheel set contacted the center sill of the car causing a slow friction burn through on the remaining axle.  The train stopped at Mile 52.25 and nosed in the passing siding at South Lagrange to lift several loads for the chipper.  After lifting the loads on their nose they backed out of the siding and continued north another 1.2 miles where they stopped again.  They shoved the loads, which were on their nose, into the south end of the chip loading track at Mile 53.47, South Lagrange.  They backed out of the chip siding after dropping the chip loads and continued their trip north.  When the 16th car in the train encountered the facing point switch at Mile 53.47 whe remaining axle burnt (broke) through and derailed GATX 19088.  GATX 19088 rolled to the east side of the track striking (cornering) one of the loaded chip cars they had previously set on the chip siding.  The impact slightly damaged a vent located on the top of the tank car.  A very small amount of disel fuel dripped from the vent apparently caused by the impact (stress) of striking the equipment on the adjacent track.  The dripping product was contained by use of a bucket.  The small amount which actually dripped on the ground prior to placement of the container was cleaned up by use of pads.
DEFECTIVE DEVICE BY SHIPPER.

column168: Driver connected receivers hose to the trailer female discharge fitting and started flow of product. On observing product drippig from trailer fitting, driver shut down unloading, bled off pressure and proceeded to drain product from hose. On attempting to lift hose the cam lock fitting arm broke, allowing hose to disconnect, spilling product. Material contained on delivery pad (impervious surface) and cleaned-up.
column169: Procedures for inspection of discharge line reviewed with driver. Cause of driver receiving 2 small spots of acid on hand was the result of improper wearing of acid gloves. He was re-trained on proper wearing of gloves. He was immediately treated at clinic and returned to duty with no loss of work.

column168: BOOKING WAS MADE OCT 24, 2005 WITH NO INDICATION OF HAZMAT LADING.  CONTAINER HDMU2100084 WAS INGATED TO BNSF HOUSTON ON NOV 28 WITHOUT PLACARDS AND WITHOUT CARRIERS BEING NOTIFIED OF HAZMAT LADING.  CONTAINER WAS MOVED ON THE RAIL TO LOS ANGELES (HOBART) RAIL TERMINAL AND TRUCKED TO CALIFORNIA UNITED TERMINAL AND ACCEPTED AS NON HAZMAT ON DEC 8.  CONTAINER WAS LOADED TO THE VESSEL ON DEC 12 AT 0900.  CARRIER (HYUNDAI) WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 ON DEC 12 THAT THERE WERE 10 DRUMS OF REGULATED HAZMAT (UN1993) IN THE CONTAINER.  HYUNDAI NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL AND VESSEL.  DANGEROUS CARGO MANIFEST WAS UPDATED, VESSEL CREW WAS NOTIFIED, AND PLACARDS WERE SUPPLIED TO THE VESSEL FOR THIS UNIT.  STOWAGE WAS ACCEPTABLE ONBOARD THE VESSEL FOR THIS COMMODITY AND NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED.
column169: BETTER TRAINING AND BETTER COMMUNICATION BETWEEN SHIPPERS, FORWARDERS, AND CARRIERS.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading one wet carton containing one, 3.6 liter bottle was discovered leaking.  Approximately, 3.6 liters of free product were released.  Apparently, the release was due to a puncture by a forklift.  BAX Global personnel performed the cleanup using gloves and absorbent materials.  The cleanup materials, wet carton and leaking bottle were placed into one, eighty-five gallon plastic overpack drum which will be held at the terminal pending shipper instructions.  The remainder of the shipment will be forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the result of a puncture by a forklift, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: Our phenolic resin plant has been in operation since September of 2004 at 2999 John Stevens Way in Hoquiam, WA. During which time we have received several loads of phenol in truck load quantities, using air pressure to unload it. We have been using the same technique to unload phenol from railcars since August 2005.      On December 1, 2005 we were attempting to unload phenol from railcar #GATX2829 into our phenol stroage tank. When the flow failed to start we presumed the line was plugged and opened the vent valve until the pressure gauge on the railcar indicated zero; we later discovered it actually had close to 18 psi. We disconnected the fill hose and noticed the phenol in the short (approximately two feet long) piece of pipe leading to the railcar was plugged solid with frozen phenol. We then used a steam lance, blowing hot steam onto the outside of the pipe. Since phenol thaws at 105 F, when it was warmed up, phenol came out of that piece of pipe with the force provided by the air pressure inside the railcar. We quickly fabricated something like a "Shepard's hook", and shut off the phenol flow by closing the valve from the railcar. The total time of flow was probably around five minutes with the volume around 375 gallons. There were no injuries associated with the release.
column169: We are going to have more "chemical specific" training on the safe handling and unloading of phenol. Additionally, we will heat trace the fill and vent lines preventing the freezing conditions that plugged the lines leading to this incident. Our procedures now include checking the railcar pressure by slowly loosening the bolts on the manhole cover to ensure there is no pressure.

column168: The material was dispatched to deliver at a company directly adjacent to the propery where spill occurred.  The driver had delivered to this consignee previously but, not the company where the load was actually supposed to be delivered.  This is a remote location and there were no personnel from the consignee at the site.  Driver hooked hose to a HCL tank (where the driver previouly had unloaded) and began to unload.  Driver went to the cab of the truck and sat in seat to do paperwork and at some point looked into the mirror and noticed product spewing from top of recieving tank.  Driver immediately closed the external valves on the trailer and the load line.  The driver then called the carrier to report the incident.  The drain valve for the containment had been left open and approximately 85 gallons of HCL was released to the land.  A clean-up company was sent to the scene and product on the ground was neutralized and standing liquid in the containment area was vaccumed up.  All material was sent to a disposal company for proper disposal.
column169: The driver is now in a remedial training program where he will recieve extensive training on proper loading and unloading procedures of all products.  The carrier has reviewed the procedures for handling all corrosive products and some changes were made to these procedures.  No unloading will be allowed at remote locations unless there is a representative of the consignee available to accept the shipment.

Shipment was being delivered to truck at carrier's cargo warehouse. While being delivered onto the truck, the package torn when the forklift driver passed by another cargo package( wooden box)  already on the  truck. The forklift driver did not allow enough clearance when loading the package,and the package was torn o the side. The shipper had loaded the plastic bags onto an overpack consisting of 30 plastic bags on each skid. The plastic bags were also extending over the width of the skid and extending below the base of the skid. It was in the area that the damge occured.   The incident was reported to the local FAA office at ORD  O'HARE). The primary cause was deemed to be forklift accident.   The incident was reported to Lufthansa Cargo headquarters recommending shipper not have an overlap of the skid when making an overpack of plastic bags.
column169: Forklift driver advised to be more careful when loading hazmat.   Lufhtansa Cargo head office advised to have shipper not overlap base of skid with these bags of hazmat.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one leaking 30-gallon plastic drum was discovered.  Approximately half an ounce of free product was released.  The release was due to a defective drum.  BAX Global/The Brink's Company personnel performed the initial cleanup using absorbents.  The cleanup materials and leaking drum were placed into a 85-gallon overpack drum pending shipper instructions.  First Response, Inc. of Goodlettsville, TN was contracted to repackage the remaining product in the defective drum.  First Response, Inc. transferred the remaining product in the defective drum to a new drum and the drum was returned to the shipper. Two drums of waste were generated during the cleanup and held at the BAX Global/The Brink's Company facility in Nashville, TN pending disposal coordination. No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been the cause of a defective drum, no plans currently exise to prevent recurrence.

column168: A LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED WHEN THE TRAILER ON DOOR #36 WAS OPENED FOR UNLOADING.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AS ISOPROPANOL BY THE DMP CREW AND THE SPILLED QUANTITY, 5 LITERS, WAS ABSORBED AND PROCESSED ALONG WITH ONE OF THE INNER PACKS WHICH WAS SATURATED WITH ALCOHOL.  THE DMR INCIDENT NUMBER IS US9469200512080003.  THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL, 25 LITERS, IS BEING HELD PENDING FURTHER COMMUNICATION FROM HMSC.  THE PACKAGE CONSISTS OF 30 ONE LITER PLASTIC BOTTLES OF ISOPROPANOL.  THEY WERE PACKED IN FIBERBOARD INNER CARTONS, 6 BOTTLES PER CARTON.  THERE WERE 5 INNER CARTONS IN ONE FIBERBOARD OUTER CARTON.  THE BOTTLES ARE LABELED "MG CHEMICALS ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL 99.953% PURE ANHYDROUS."  THE INNER CARTONS ARE LABELED "ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL CAT NO: 824-1L" AND "CONSUMER COMMODITY ORM-D."  THE OUTER CARTON IS A REUSED BOX WITH NO INDICATION OF HAZARDOUS CONTENTS.
column169: SHIPPER NEEDS TO SECURE CAPS ON BOTTLES AND PROVIDE ABSORBANT PACKING MATERIAL.  SHIPPER NEEDS TO MARK AND LABEL HAZMATS AS REQUIRED.

column168: The subject drum was received on 12/22/05 at the Onyx,ten-day transfer facility located in Sauget, IL.  The drum was unloaded from the inbound trailer and reloaded onto an outbound trailer (078) with other containers on 12/23/05.  Trailer 078 was only partially loaded and remained parked at the loading dock (ramped area with secondary containment and blind sump) until 12/26/05.  On 12/26/05, at approximately 18:30, an employee of the transfer facility noticed material on the floor of trailer 078.  The spill was investigated and the leaking drum was identified shortly thereafter.  Clean-up procedures were initiated immediately by on-site personnel.  All spillage was contained in secondary containement.  The spilled material was solidified with oil dry and placed into DOT approved containers (two 30 gallon containers) and placed on a pallet with the now empty original container, for shipment to the final disposal facility.    The container that leaked was inspected and a small hole (approximately 2-3mm)was found on the side of the drum approximately one inch above the bottom of the drum.  The hole appeared to be the result of corrosion from inside the container.  It did not appear to be a puncture hole.
column169: The exterior of the drum appeared to be in very good shape.  The contents were not corrosive, so there was little expectation that the drum would leak.  The offerer was notified of the incident and is investigating.

column168: Ferrellgas Driver George Cleaver was driving a bobtail on County Road 200 East. The bobtail slid on ice as he was slowing for an intersection. The right front tire got off on the shoulder. He stayed off, headed for a field when the back of the truck swung around, unit rolled over side to side, came to rest on passenger side.  Driver had 2 inch laceration to right hand, stitches at Whitan Hospital in Lebanan, released. There were no other vehicles involved.     When the truck rolled, the liquid unloading line between the meter and the hose  twisted at the threads which caused it to leak propane vapor. Valves were immediately turned off to stop the leak.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: The driver of the propane truck parked the truck, removed the delivery hose from the hose reel and layed the hose on the stationary propane tank but did not connect it. The propane that was contained in the hose released without incident.
column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed.

column168: Trailer arrived in Jacksonville Florida from Atlanta Ga. at 0740. When doors to trailer were openned a leak was discovered coming from a 55 gal drum located at the rear of the trailer. A environmental recovery contractor removed the drum from the trailer and placed it in a recovery drum. They then cleaned up the spill and neutralized the area.The material was disposed of by a licensed environmental recovery company.
column169: A safety meeting was held with the dock workers who loaded the drum on the trailer. Also operating procedures have been changed on how drums are loaded and secured on trailers.

column168: 1 Tote container was being delivered to customer on private property. Driver was lowering container from a trailer using a power lift gate. The container fell from the lift and struck the ground. Poly bladder ruptured. Material was contained to local area, and dammed from spreading. Concrete surface vacuumed and cleaned with detergent. Residue drummed for disposal by third party responder.
column169: Discussion documented with driver and customer involved concerning the use of lift gate equipment with bulk containers. The customer requested tailgate delivery due to the facility not being equipped with a trailer dock. Discontinue the practice of tailgate delivery of bulk containers.

SHIPMENT ON CCX PRO NUMBER 570-021395 ARRIVED AT KEOKUK, IA TERMINAL FROM SALEM, IL ON TRL 315-5595 ON MORNING OF 12/7/05.  SHIPMENT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY TO ROSEVILLE, IL.. UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE ? AVON ROOSEVILLE VET SERVICE THE CARTON SHOWED SIGNS OF BEING WET ON THE BOTTOM.  UPON INSPECTION IT WAS NOTED THAT ONE OF THE 5 LITER JUGS WAS SEAPING LIQUID FROM A SEAM IN THE BOTTOM OF THE JUG WHICH WAS A PLASTIC CONTAINER.  THERE WERE NO HOLES OR PUNCTURE MARKS IN THIS CONTAINER.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND RETURNED TO THE CCX KEOKUK, IA TERMINAL.  THE LEAKING PLASTIC JUG WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN IN THE OUTER FIBERBOARD CARTON CONTAINER TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL AT KEOKUK, IA TERMINAL THE CTN WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  UPON ARRIVAL AT KEOKUK, IA TERMINAL THE CTN WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.
column169: I HAVE NO EXPLANATION FOR THIS LEAK OTHER THAN POSSIBLY THE BITTER COLD WEATHER.  PLASTIC CONTAINERS SUCH AS THIS ARE ROUTINELY USED AND HOLD UP EXCEPTIONALLY WELL AS A RULE.

Shipment of 40 bags was loaded in North Carolina and secured with load-lock bars. During transportation to Oregon, two bags rubbedd against each other and against the load-lock bars, causing a small hole in each of the bags, releasing less than 100 lbs. of product. The spilled material was confined to the trailer and cleaned up by a Hazmat contractor. The spilled material was containerized for transportation and disposal.
column169: A cardboard sheet could have been used as a sacrificial material to minimize the abrasive action of the load-lock bar.

column168: Our driver went to pick up a loaded cargo tank that was being relayed at our operating center.  When he arrived at our facility, he found that the cargo tank was leaking from the belly of the trailer.  The driver put spill pads down to contain it and put a bucket under the leak.  HMHTTC was called to clean up the spill and stand by while our personnel transferred the product to another trailer.  The product was successfully transferred. Our maintenance facility inspected the barrel of the cargo tank after the incident and found some stress cracks on the bottom of the barrel.  The trailer is still in our shop for the required maintenance and annual inspections before being dispatched again.
column169: The cracks would not have been discovered until the barrel was inspected during the annual inspection which was due by the 31st of January.  Some product that was transported in the trailer may have caused the cracks.  We rely on corrosion reference books and shipper testing (when available) to help in determining container compatibility for products we haul.  It is difficult to get exact information because of chemical combinations.

column169: The following corrective/preventative actions are being taken:    1. Incident has been entered into our "Corrective Action Process." column168: A dry van was presented to the shipper for shipment of drums of Sulfuric Acid.  Van was not wide enough to accomidate palatized shipment.  Drums were removed from pallets and stood free standing in the trailer.  A load lock was installed in front of and behind drums.  While inroute driver had to brake hard and some drums shifted forward causing the front load lock to giveway. Drums continued forward contacting the bulk head of the trailer causing it to giveway and break loose from the front of the trailer.  Three drums went outside the trailer and rolled into the ditch but did not leak. Two drums wedged between the front of the trailer and the back of the tractor.  One drum punctured on the bottom and leaked out most of the material.  The second drum was punctured at the top and leaked two or three gallons.  The driver who is a volunteer fireman recognized the hazard and borrowed a shovel from passer by and formed a containment around the leak. The driver called his dispatcher and I was called. Upon notice I looked up the number and called the Williamsburg County of South Carolina Sheriff department and notified them of the incident.  My next call was to EMI a national emergancy responce angency to arrange a team for clean up and remediantion.  A team was dispacted from Charleston, SC and a wrecker service from near by was contacted to assist.  The drums were removed from the ditch and reloaded the leaking drum was put into an overpack container and reloaded.  The shipment was escorted about 10 miles to the consignee and off loaded in their receiving area.  The EMI team continued with the sight clean up the following day and an estimated 4 yards of soil were replaced and the EMI team took the contaiminated soil for proper disposal.  Temporary repairs were made to the trailer and it was tranported to a vendor for repair.
column169: Going forward dispatch rules have been modified to ensure proper dispatch equipment sized for shipment configuration.  Also loading proceedures have been reviewed to ensure proper securement of all free standing cargo.

column168: AN OPERATOR SPOTTED A TANK TRUCK AT THE LOADING RACK.  HE SET THE GALLON METER, EQUIPPED WITH AUTOMATIC SHUTOFF, AT THE RACK AND BEGAN LOADING AT 4:00 P.M.  AT 05:05 P.M. THE OPERATOR OBSERVED MATERIAL SPILLING FROM THE TANK TRUCK.  THE PUMP WAS TURNED OFF.  DURATION OF RELEASE WAS 5 MINUTES.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY BELOW THE TRUCK, FLOWING INTO A NEARBY GRAVEL AREA.  AS A PRECAUTION A PLUG WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC DRAIN PIPE IN THE GRAVEL AREA THAT IS PART OF THE IN-PART STORM WATER SYSTEM.  NO MATERIAL MADE IT TO THE STORM SEWER OR LEFT THE SITE.  (NOTE: STORM WATER FROM THE FACILITY IS NORMALLY PUMPED TO THE IN-HOUSE PROCESS SEWER TREATMENT SYSTEM WHICH DISCHARGES TO THE MUNICIPAL POTW).  MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY WAS RECOVERED ALONG WITH MATERIAL THAT ACCUMULATED IN A LOW SPOT IN THE ADJACENT GRAVEL AREA AND WAS PUMPED TO A <90 DAY RCRA STORAGE TANK.  THE INITIAL DETERMINATION WAS THAT AT LEAST 250 GALLONS HAD BEEN SPILLED, EXCEEDING THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ) FOR THIS MATERIAL.
column169: METER AUTOMATIC SHUTOFF FUNCTION WAS REPAIRED.  OPERATOR WAS GIVEN FOLLOW-UP TRAINING EMPHASIZING THE NEED TO PAY CLOSER ATTENTION DURING LOADING OPERATION.

While refueling his tractor trailer at a roadisde truckstop, our driver noticed an orange liquid dripping from the underside of his trailer and onto the asphalt. The driver immediately reported the incident to our traffic manager and at the same time stopped refueling and moved the truck to an isolated area within the truck stop. The driver used his spill response materials to capture and control furhter drips. Roughly an hour after noticing the dripping, our driver reported that the dripping had stopped.     The operator of the truck stop was notified of the situation, as was the Indiana Department of Environmental Managemment(IDEM)at(317)308-3377. The IDEM contact was Mr. Jason Sewell, who assigned the incident the case number "2005-12-108."    Private emergency response contractors were dispatched to the scene. Upon arrival, our driver shared the shipping papers with the contractor and together they determined the most likely source for the release. Using the appropriate monitoring devices, the response contractor confirmed that the trailer was safe for entry of his crew to identify and control the leaking container. After re-positioning a number of containers (55 gallon drums) the offending container was located, identified, and overpacked for safe transport for appropriate disposal.     The container was determined to have leaked as the result of a pin-hole in the base of the container. The actual cause of the pin-hole is not yet known. The remaining iquid in the container was measured and it was determined that the maximum volume that could have been release was 10 gallons.     The material released consisted of a mixture of alcohol and xylene. No deterioration of the asphalt or other property was noticed.
column169: The specific reason for the pin-hole release has yet to be answered conclusively. No evidence was found that would indicate the cause for the leak. No physical "trauma" to the container could be found. However, the container supplier has been contacted and steps are being taken to try and determine the cause for the leak and to prevent future similar incidents. The container supplier's quality control and testing process is being scrutinized.     Secondary containment is being considered for our tractor trailers. Contractors have been engaged to determine the most effective means for providing the containment for our vehicles.

column168: Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank using a pump.  When customer tank was registering 80% full, it started to foam over.  Driver was standing by the customer valve at the time so he shut that valve to prevent more product from entering the tank.  As he went to shut trailer valve and the fitting blew off the fill line hook-up and product splashed out.  Driver was splashed in eyes.  He was immediately taken to a water hose to flush his eyes and then to an eyewash station to flush for 15 minutes.  He was checked out by an onsite nurse who sent him to the hospital to be checked out.  In the meantime, I talked to a toxicologist from the shipper and they said as long as the driver got his eyes washed out as directed, he should be okay.  The hospital checked out the driver and released him back to the mill to complete the delivery.
column169: An unstable fill line with a little extra pressure on it may have caused the problem but the main issue is that the driver was not wearing the proper PPE prescribed.  He said he had safety glasses on but they were blown off.  He did not have his face shield down.  His work assignment called for a chemical suit and goggles along with his other basic PPE.  He chose not to wear it.  Driver has been counseled and has received additional training and evaluation.  A message went out to our entire fleet addressing the importance of wearing PPE.

column168: THIS IS A DESCRIPTION OF AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING A CARDINAL HEALTH (CAH) VEHICLE.  THE CAH VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON 6TH STREET WHERE IT STOPPED AT A STOP LIGHT.  WHILE STOPPED AT THE STOP LIGHT, A MINIVAN WHICH WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND CROSSED OVER ITS LANE AND STRUCK THE CAH VEHICLE HEAD-ON.  THE CAH VEHICLE WAS THEN REAR-ENDED BY A TRUCK TRAVELING WESTBOUND.  THIS CAUSED THE CAH VEHICLE'S TRUCK BED COVER TO OPEN AND THE CARGO (AMMO CANS) WERE EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE AMMO CANS AND THEIR CONTENTS REMAINED INTACT DESPITE THE COLLISION.  THE CAH VEHICLE WAS CARRYING SIX PACKAGES AT THE TIME.  FOUR OF THESE PACKAGES WERE LIMITED QUANTITY RETURN PACKAGES FROM OUR CUSTOMERS, AND TWO OF THE PACKAGES WERE OUTBOUND PACKAGES.  THE OUTBOUND PACKAGES, CUMULATIVELY, CONTAINED 600 MCI OF TC-99M.  SURVEYS AND WIPES WERE PERFORMED ON THE CAH VEHICLE AND THE ROADWAY.  BOTH THE VEHICLE AND THE ROADWAY WERE AT BACKGROUND.  THERE ARE TWO IMPROTANT ITEMS TO NOTE ABOUT THIS ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER OF THE MINIVAN, WHICH CROSSED LANES, DIED AS A RESULT OF INJURIES INCURRED FROM THIS ACCIDENT.  ALSO FOR APPROXIMATELY THREE HOURS THE AMMO CANS WERE IN THE SECURE POSSESSION OF THE LAWRENCE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  PRIOR TO TAKING THE AMMO CANS INTO THEIR POSSESSION THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SURVEYED THE PACKAGES FOR CONTAMINATION.  THEY THEN PLACED THEM IN A SECURE AREA OF THEIR FIRE DEPARTMENT UNTIL THE CAH RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER ARRIVED TO TAKE THEM INTO HIS POSSESSION AND RETURN THEM TO THE PHARMACY.
column169: DUE TO THE LARGE VOLUME OF DELIVERY VEHICLES UTILIZED BY CARDINAL HEALTH, ACCIDENTS OCCUR FROM TIME TO TIME.  CARDINAL HEATLH IS CONSTANTLY WORKING TO IMPROVE OUR DRIVER TRAINING AND SAFETY AWARENESS PROGRAMS.  IN THIS CASE THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT WAS NOT DUE TO ANY NEGLIGENCE ON THE PART OF OUR DRIVER.  WE COMMIT TO CONTINUING DRIVER SAFETY AND AWARENESS EDUCATION IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE REGULATORY AGENCIES.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver was traveling on Hwy 20 in Niceville FL.  Driver of 2006 Chevy Pickup truck crossed the center line and struck Florida Rock & Tank Lines tanker trailer.  Axles were knocked off trailer causing trailer to become unstable and roll over onto left side.  Both the tractor and trailer are a total loss.  Approximately 1000 gallons of gasoline spilled onto roadway.  The area of leakage was at the #1 compartment due to an abrasion of the tanker body of approx 0.75 inch diameter at the #1 compartment.  All spilled product was contained on the asphalt roadway by Florida Rock & Tank Lines personnel and by emergency personnel.  Axles impacted a parked vehicle and a reality sign causing significant damage to both.  Florida Rock & Tank Lines tanker driver and pickup truck driver both had injuries as a result of the crash, not as a result of the hazardous material.  Pickup truck driver was life-flighted to hospital with head trauma.
column169: Accident was non-preventable for Florida Rock & Tank Lines.  Other vehicle crossed the center line and our driver was unable to avoid impact.    We recommend stricter accountability and penalties for reckless and aggressive drivers as this behavior places the general public in harms way.

column168: AT 05:04 PM ON 12/14/05, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT MIKE ROGERS, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, HAD ADVISED TRAIN CREW AT COADY YARD HAD REPORTED TANK UTLX 12196 TO BE POSSIBLY VENTING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CHECK CAR RECORDS INDICATED CAR TO BE LOCATED IN TRACK 41, COADY YARD; BAYTOWN, TX.  UPON BEING ADVISED, MGR. LERCH REQUESTED THE RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  ON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CAR, MGR. LERCH NOTED THE FOUR BOLT OUTBOARD SIDE BLIND FLANGE UNSECURED.  THREE STUDS WERE LOOSE, WITH THE FOURTH STUD MISSING A NUT.  ADDITIONALLY, THE FOUR STUDS ATTACHING THE AIR VALVE TO THE MANWAY WERE ALL IN POSITION, NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  MGR. LERCH REPLACED THE MISSING NUT, AND TIGHTENED ALL FITTINGS.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WAS NO LIQUID PRODUCT RELEASED.  PRODUCT HAD OFF GASSED WHILE BEING SWITCHED, WHICH THE CREW REPORTED SEEING.  AT 0900HRS ON 12-19-05 MESSAGE LEFT FOR JIM TAPSCOTT, FACILITY MANAGER OF TATE & LYLE ADVISING HIM OF NOTED EXCEPTIONS, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.
column169: PRACTICE PROPER POST INSPECTION OF CAR PRIOR TO RELEASING FOR TRANSPORTATION.      NARRI: 5(4+3+0) X (2+0) = 70      CODE(S): 255

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM ON DECEMBER 14 2005 A TANKER TRAILER OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC (CHESI) EXPERIENCED A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SPECIFICATION USED FUEL OIL) FROM A BULK PACKAGE.  AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE THE VEHICLE WAS STOPPED AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT AT THE INTERSECTION OF CASH CORNER AND MAIN STREET IN SOUTH PORTLAND, MAINE.  WHEN THE VEHICLE BEGAN TO MOVE FORWARD, PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED RUNNING DOWN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PAVED ROAD SURFACE.  THERE WERE NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE.  THE DRIVER DETERMINED THAT THE REAR DOME COVER POPPED OPEN ALLOWING BETWEEN 75-100 GALLONS OF SPECIFICATION USED FUEL OIL TO SLOSH OUT OF THE DOME.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE AREA, DEPLOYED AVAILABLE ABSORBENT MATERIALS, RETRIEVED THE SHIPPING PAPERS AND NOTIFIED THE APPROPRIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES INCLUDING THE SOUTH PORTLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE MAINE STATE POLICE AND THE MAINE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.  IN ADDITION, THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER AND AN IN-HOUSE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED AND ARRIVED ON-SITE WITHIN 15 MINUTES OF THE RELEASE.  THE IN-HOUSE RESPONSE CREW CONDUCTED A THROUGH SPILL CLEAN UP OPERATION UNDER THE OBSERVATION AND DIRECTION OF THE MAINE DEP.  ALL RECOVERED PRODUCT AND SPILL DEBRIS ASSOCIATED WITH THE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED IN APPROPRIATE CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL AT FULLY PERMITTED HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE REPOSE ACTIVITIES, THE VEHICLE IN QUESTION WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TENSION CONTROL DEVICE OF THE FAILED DOME COVER WAS OUT OF ADJUSTMENT AND THE RUBBER GASKET WAS IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT.
column169: IN RESPONSE TO THE EVENT, THE VEHICLE IN QUESTION WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND A NEW HOME COVER ASSEMBLY WAS INSTALLED.  IN ADDITION, A SECONDARY LOCKING MECHANISM HAS BEEN ADDED TO INSURE A REPEAT INCIDENT DOES NOT OCCUR.  WE ALSO INTEND TO INCREASE THE FREQUENCY OF THE VISUAL INSPECTION OF THIS AND ALL SIMILAR TANKS TO A BI-ANNUAL SCHEDULE TO INSURE THE TENSION DEVICES ARE PROPERLY ADJUSTED AND FUNCTIONAL.  THE INDIVIDUAL RESPONSIBLE FOR SECUREMENT AND TRANSPORTATION OF THIS VEHICLE WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON PROPER DOME LID AND VALVE INSPECTION AND SECUREMENT TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE SPILLS RESULTING FROM IMPROPER CLOSURE.

column168: CN SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT AND VAPORS COMING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR SHPX 204328 WHILE PASSING THE STATIONARY TANK CAR ON ADJACENT TRACK DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS, AT CN MARKHAM YARD, EAST HAZEL CREST, IL.  TWO CREWMEMBERS REPORTED INHALING PRODUCT VAPORS AND REQUESTED MEDICAL TREATMENT.  EMPLOYEES TRANSPORTED TO AN AREA HOSPITAL, TREATED AND LATER RELEASED.  ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED AND CN HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED NOTING FOUR OF THE SIX MANWAY BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  MANWAY BOLTS TIGHTENED AND TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER P7386 WHICH HAD ARRIVED FROM THE FEDEX FREIGHT IN PHOENIX, AZ WE NOTICED A BOX CAUGHT BETWEEN TWO PALLETS.  THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS WET IN A 1 FOOT CIRCLE AROUND IT.  WE PULLED OUT THE PALLET THAT WAS HOLDING IT IN PLACE AND PUT DOWN KITTY LITTER AROUND IT TO SOAK UP ANY STILL ON THE FLOOR.  WE PUT THE DAMAGED CASE IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM.  THE BOX THAT WAS DAMAGED HAD 4-1 GALLON JUGS INSIDE.  ONE OF THE JUGS HAD SPLIT OPEN DOWN THE SIDE SPILLING OUT ALL THE CONTENTS.
column169: SENT PICTURES TO FEDEX FREIGHT IN PHOENIX, AZ.  RECEIVED A RESPONSE FROM ROGER MACIAS IN PHOENIX THAT THEY WOULD TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION AND TO INSURE THIS WOULD NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column168: Driver was backing the bobtail on an ice covered driveway. The truck slid off the driveway and struck a large dumpster. The impact loosened a coupling on the liquid gas line releasing apx 5 gallons of propane without incident.
column169: After such an accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: ON DECEMBER 5, 2005 OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING PROPANE DELIVERIES TO OUR RESIDENTIAL AND COMMERCIAL CUSTOMERS. HE WAS IN TRANSIT BETWEEN CARTHAGE, NC AND ROBBINS, NC TRAVELING ON PLANK ROAD. IT WAS RAINING AT THE TIME. AS OUR DRIVER CAME TO A RIGHT HAND CORNER OF THE ROAD, HIS RIGHT FRONT TIRE DROPPED OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER. HE OVERCORRECTED AND VEERED TOO FAR LEFT, CROSSED THE OPPOSING LANE AND ONTO THE SHOULDER ON THE OPPOSITE (LEFT) SIDE OF THE ROAD. HE TRIED TO CORRECT HIS ACTIONS BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. DUE TO PRODUCT SURGE, THE HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY OF A CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE AND HIS WHEEL DROPPING ONTO THE LEFT SHOULDER, HIS VEHICLE ROLLED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE AND SLID DOWN THE ROADWAY. AS THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED, THE DELIVERY HOSE REEL STRUCK THE ROADWAY SURFACE CAUSING A VERY SMALL CRACK TO FORM IN A 1/4 " SCHEDULE 80 ELBOW AT THE PIPE THREADS. THIS SMALL ELBOW IS USED IN CONNECTING A HYDROSTATIC RELIEF VALVE TO THE DELIVERY HOSE. THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER 1.5 TIMES AND SLID DOWN THE ROAD FOR APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET.   ONLY THE PRODUCT IN THE DELIVERY HOSE WAS LOST, ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF PROPANE, DUE TO VALVES THAT ISOLATED THE DELIVERY HOSE FROM THE REST OF THE PIPING SYSTEM ON THE VEHICLE. THE RELEASE LASTED 3.5 HOURS. THE LENGTH OF TIME THE RELEASE LASTED WAS DUE TO THE VERY SMALL SIZE OF THE CRACK IN THE PIPING. DUE TO THE SMALL SIZE OF THE LEAK AND PROPANE'S PHYSICAL PROPERTIES, NOTHING WAS DONE TO MITIGATE THE LEAK OTHER THAN MAKING SURE THE VALVE TO THE HOSE REEL WAS CLOSED. THE PROPANE GAS VAPORS WERE DISPERSING AS QUICKLY AS THE LIQUID WAS VAPORIZING.

During a routine inspection of the warehouse waste transfer holding area by Univar personnel, one open head drum was noticed to have a small leak around the top ring.  The leak (estimated 1 gallon) was contained in the immediate area on the warehouse concrete floor.  The generator had used a poly liner inside the metal drum and had draped it over the top, sealed the drum with the lid and ring.    Univar (in-house) employees overpacked the leaking drum, plus two additional drums of the same material.  The spill was absorbed with floor dry.  The warehouse floor area was cleaned, neutralized and all waste materials including the contaminated pallet were containerized for subsequent management.

column168: Driver arrived at customer location and contacted site personnel to ensure that the entire load would fit into their above-ground tank.  Site personnel stated the load would fit and signed our "Product Integrity Form" indicating the same.  As the driver was pumping off the product, the tank overfilled and approximately 15 gallons was spilled onto the blacktop surface.  The customer's maintenance supervisor was called to the scene and customer was notified.  Product was cleaned up by internal employees.
column169: Customer must keep better records of product going into and coming out of their tank so that they know how much is there.    Design above ground tanks so that it is possible to "see" how much product is in the tank, or design tanks so that personnel can safely stick the tank to determine the amount of product contained in the tank.

column168: 16DEC'05 @ 0300-0330L  THE JAL CARGO SUPERVISOR WAS SUMMONED BY CS AGENT CHECKING-IN THE CARGO AFTER ARRIVAL BECAUSE OF A STRONG ODOR EMANATING FROM THE BOX.  AFTER FURTHER INSPECTION, NEITHER THE JAL CARGO SUPERVISOR NOR THE CS AGENT COULD DETECT ANY VISIBLE DAMAGE/DISCREPANCY TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE CARTON BOX.  THE BOX WAS STORED SEPARATELY FROM OTHER CARGO FOR CONSIGNEE PICKUP.  16DEC'06 @0830-0930L  THE CONSIGNEE/AGENT CLEARED CUSTOMS WITHOUT PHYSICAL INSPECTION AND BROUGHT THE ITEM TO THEIR WAREHOUSE WHICH IS WITHIN AIRPORT PREMISES.  JAL CARGO STAFF WAS SUMMONED TO OBSERVE OPENING OF CARTON BOX.  AT THIS TIME A DARK LINE ON THE BOTTOM EDGE OF THE BOX COULD BE OBSERVED.  THE BOX CAME WITH ITS BOTTOM EDGES SEALED WITH CLEAR TAPE.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED, IT APPEARED THAT THE LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM 2 1L PLASTIC BOTTLES.  THERE WERE NO HOLES ON THE BOX.  IT WAS APPARENT THAT THE APPLICATION OF THE CLEAR TAPE HELPED IN PREVENTING THE LIQUID FROM ESCAPING OUTSIDE THE BOX.  16DEC'06@1030L SEVERAL ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT FAA/HNL BY PHONE WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  MESSAGES WERE LEFT ON THE VOICE MAIL.  EMAIL TO FAA/HNL WAS DISPATCHED DESCRIBING THE INCIDENT.  20DEC'05-THE CARTON BOX WAS TO THE ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE AFTER RECEIVING WORD FROM FAA/HNL THAT IT WAS OKAY TO RELEASE IF PHOTOS HAVE BEEN TAKEN.  PHOTOS WERE TAKEN.
column169: ACTION SHOULD BE TAKEN AT POINT OF ORIGIN.

column168: 12/30/05, 5:45AM: WHILE PERFORMING ROUTINE SWITCHING IN PORT NEWARK (NJ) YARD, CR CREW YPPN83 RAN THROUGH A SWITCH AND DERAILED FOUR RAIL CARS WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH ON TRACK #9.  FROM SOUTH TO NORTH, THE CARS INVOLVED WERE: ACFX 67880 (EMPTY, L/C PLASTICS), SCMX 2545 (LOAD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS) DUPX 21056 (LOAD, NON-REGULATED LIQUID ADDITIVE), AND GATX 7313 (RESIDUE L/C SULFURIC ACID).  TANK CAR SCMX 2545 (LOAD, PETROLEUM DISTILLATES NOS, 3, UN 1268, II, NON-JACKETED DOT SPECIFICATION 111A100W1), DERAILED, DETRUCKED UNDERNEATH THE PORT STREET OVERPASS.  NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  CAR RECEIVED HEAVY DAMAGE TO BL SIDE DUE TO IMPACT WITH A PORT STREET WOVERPASS BRIDGE EMBUNKMENT.  ADDITIONALLY ENCOUNTERED HEAVY DAMAGE IN THE LEFT SIDE, LOWER MIDDLE AREA, DUE IMPACT WITH RAIL, TRUCK ASSEMBLIES, B-END STILL ALSO BROKEN OFF AT END OF CAR.  DUE TO ITS POSITION OF REST AGAINST THE OVERPASS SUPPORTS, IT WAS DECIDED TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS IN ORDER TO RERAIL THE CAR WITH GREATER EASE AND SAFETY.  THREE LOADS (TOTALLING 17,400 GALLONS) WERE REMOVED FROM THE CAR.  CAR WAS THEN RERAILED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT AND REMAINED ON SITE UNTIL COMPLETE CONTENTS OF CAR COULD BE REMOVED (DUE TO TANK AVAILABILITY).  FINAL TWO LOADS (TOTALLING 6695 GALLONS) WERE REMOVED ON TUESDAY, 1/3/06.  CAR WAS THEN FILLED AND FLUSHED WITH SOAP AND WATER SOLUTION.  CAR THEN SECURED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO CR'S OAK ISLAND CAR SHOP FACILITY TO AWAIT DISPOSITION.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column168: 12/30/05: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:25AM, WHILE INSPECTING RAIL CARS ON TRACK #1 CLASS FOR OUTBOUND TRAIN, CR MECHANICAL INSPECTOR NOTED TANK CAR PPGX 5757 (LOAD, 1,1,1-TRICHOLOROETHANE, 6.1, UN 2831, PG III, RQ) WITH ICE-LIKE MATERIAL RUNNING DOWN THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR, IN AND AROUND THE SIDE LADDER.  CR RISK MANAGEMENT A. RICHTER, AND ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REACT NOTIFIED.  PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER SEAL (INTACT) "PPG 083302" WAS REMOVED AND FURTHER INSPECTION BY CR'S A. RICHTER AND REACT'S R. GOULD NOTED LIQUID LEAK ORIGINATING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR, INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, AT THE LIQUID LINE VALVE, AT THE VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE (SPITTING FROM BETWEEN THE SECUREMENT FLANGES, JUST BELOW THE VALVE OPERATING MECHANISM.) ALL FOUR SECUREMENT NUTS FOR SAID FLANGE WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, AND WERE SECURED AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION, SECURING THE LEAK.  REACT APPLIED SEAL "REACT 000298" TO THE CLOSED PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  AREA WHERE PRODUCT HAD CONTACTED THE GROUND WAS REMEDIATED.  TANK CAR WAS CUT OUT OF CR'S CA-11, AND PLACED ON THE BUDD TRACK NEAR THE ENGINE HOUSE.  PRODUCT THAT HAD ICED UP ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR WAS SCRAPED OFF, AREA WAS WIPED DOWN WITH CHEMICAL ABSORBANT PADS, AND ALLOWED TO SIT UNTIL THE NEXT EVENING TO ALLOW SIDE OF CAR TO DRY OFF (PRODUCT HAD ALREADY BEGUN TO EVAPORATE FROM THE SIDE OF THE CAR).  CAR OKAYED TO BE TRANSPORTED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION ON NEXT AVAILABLE TRAIN.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column168: THE BOX OF RESIN WAS LYING ON ITS SIDE, WHICH POSSIBLY CAUSED THE LIDS OF TWO PAILS TO LEAK.  THERE WERE TWO OTHER BOXES WITH PAILS WHICH WERE LYING SIDEWAYS, THEY DID NOT LEAK.  THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED DURING TRANSIT FROM MILTON, PA TO SANTA FE SPRINGS, CA WHICH WOULD BE 2-3 DAYS.
column169: THE PACKAGES DID NOT HAVE ANY ARROW SIGNS POINTING WHICH WAY THE BOXES SHOULD BE UP.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD COMMUNICATE THE RISK, ESPECIALLY CONSIDERING THE HAZARDOUS NATURE OF THE MATERIAL.  FURTHERMORE, MORE CAUTION SHOULD BE USED WHEN LOADING LIQUIDS.  USUALLY THOSE WHO HAVE EXPERIENCE WITH PAINT GENERALLY KNOW THAT CANS HAVE LIDS THAT CAN FAIL.  THUS, CAUTION NEEDS TO PAID TOWARD WHICH END OF A BOX NEEDS TO FACE UP.

column168: At approximately 1430 CST, a passing vehicle told the Werner driver that paint was leaking from the trailer. The driver pulled over and inspected the load and observed one of four drums shrink-wrapped on a pallet to be leaning onto the side of the trailer. Paint had leaked from a hole in the bottom of the drum.  The drum appeared to have been punctured by the corner of the pallet or a nail in the pallet. An estimated 5 gallons of paint had leaked onto the floor of the trailer with an estimated 2 gallons leaking from the trailer onto the asphalt roadway and adjacent shoulder.  An emergency response crew arrived onsite at approximately 1900 CST, donned Level "C" PPE and entered the trailer.  ER personnel overpacked the leaking drum and cleaned the paint from the floor of the trailer. Absorbent clay was placed on the asphalt to absorb the paint. The clay and minor amount of impacted soil was removed.  All cleanup debris was placed in a 55-gallon drum for disposal.  Cleanup was completed at 2010 CST.

THE DRUMS WERE PICKED UP FROM THE CUSTOMER LOOSE BUT IT WAS NOT DETERMINED WHETHER THEY WERE PALLETIZED BY THE SHIPPER OR BY THE CARRIER.  THE PALLET OF LOOSE DRUMS WAS LOADED IN THE TRAILER BUT WERE NOT SHRINKWRAPPED TOGETHER TO PREVENT THEM FROM FALLING NOR WERE THEY BRACED PROPERLY WHEN THEY WERE SHIPPED TO THE DESTINATION TERMINAL.  THIS RESULTED IN THE DRUMS FALLING OVER DURING TRANSIT AND A PORTION OF THE PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF THE CAP.  DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS PROBPABLY UP TO 3 HOURS TO THE LENGTH OF THE TRIP.  ONCE DISCOVERED, THE DRUMS WERE TURNED BACK UPRIGHT AND THE CAPS WERE FOUND TO BE SOLID ENOUGH TO CONTINUE ON TO THE CUSTOMER.
column169: THE PREVENT FUTURE RELEASES WE MUST ENSURE THAT LOOSE DRUMS ARE PROPERLY BRACED INSIDE OF THE TRAILER.

column168: There was no equipment failure involved.  The valve to unloaded the truck was opened by the employee without the unloading hose being connected while he was standing directly in front of the valve.  The propylene exited the valve hitting the employee in the stomach area.  Since the propylene is cooled to a liquid, the instant evaporation cooling effect caused burns.  The employee was able to close the valve, but was examined at the site and transfer to a hospital for higher skilled assistance.  He was admitted to the hospital over night.
column169: Review of the incident with employees doing this job.   Review of plant procedures to ensure truck driver presence in the unloading area of the truck.   Strengthing of the training progrms for unloaders.

column168: VEHICLE TRANSPORTING CLASS 7 HAZMAT EXPERIENCED UNEXPLAINED FIRE IN ENGINE COMPARTMENT. VEHICLE MANEUVERED OFF ROADWAY ON TO SHOULDER. DRIVER EXITED VEHICLE AND RECOVERED 13 OF 19 PACKAGES FROM REAR OF VEHICLE BEFORE FIRE REACHED THE FREIGHT. LOCAL FIRE BRIGADE 7 RESPONDED WITH ASSISTANCE OF MD STATE POLICE TROPPER AVILE. FIRE EXTINGUISHED AND VEHICLE REMOVED FROM ROADWAY BY FLATBED TOW TRUCK FROM HENRY'S WRECKER SERVICE (SILVER SPRING, MD GATHERSBURG LOCATION) VEHICLE TRANSPORTED TO MALLINCKRODT INC BELTSVILLE PHARMACY FOR INSPECTION AND PICTURES. DRIVER HAD NOTIFIED DEL-MED INC DISPATCHER AND LICENSEE TRIGGERING ACTIVATION OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN, DOT NOTIFIED BY PHONE OF INCIDENT AND RSO AND TEAM DISPATCHED TO INVESTIGATE RADIOLOGICAL IMPACT BY 1015. LICESNSEE (WRC) DISPATCHED TEAM TO SCENE OF FIRE TO MONITOR FOR RESIDUAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONTAMINATION. NO EVIDENCE OF CONTAMINATION FOUND AT SITE OF FIRE, VEHICLE TRANSFERRED TO JAY'S TOWING (ODENTON, MD) SUPERVISOR AUTHORIZED INSPECTION ASSESSMENT AND RECOVERY OPERATIONS ON VEHICLE CARCASS. NO RESIDUAL CONTAMINATION FOUND OUTSIDE INTERIOR OF VEHICLE. 6 PACKAGES OBSERVED TO HAVE MELTED INTO SOLID MASS IN REAR OF VEHICLE. INITIAL HIGHEST CONTACT READING WAS 2.2 MR/HR. DURING RECOVERY OF MATERIAL, MAXIMUM READING WAS 4.3 MR/HR. MAXIMUM READING OF VEHICLE SURFACE AS LEFT WAS 40 MR/HR. MATERIAL RECOVERED RETURNED TO LICENSEE.
column169: SINCE ORIGIN OF THE FIRE IS NOT KNOWN, IT IS DIFFUCULT TO EVALUATE HOW IT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED. VEHICLE WAS LATE MODEL MISUBISHI SUV IN GOOD CONDITION. DRIVER OPERATED THE SITUATION IN ACCORDANCE WITH TRAINING AND DELMED INC PROCEDURES FOR NOTIFICATION AND RESPONSE. VEHICLE REMOVED FROM ROAADWAY, QUICKLY EXTINGUISHED, AND MOVED TO A REMOTE LOCATION PRIOR TO HAZARD ASSESSMENT WITH SOPHISTICATED INSTRUMENTATION. FIRE BRIGADE ACTED PROPERLY FOR THE PERCEIVED HAZARD OF EMPTY HAZMAT PACKAGED NO INDIVIDUAL WOULD HAVE BEEN EXPOSED TO A RADIATION FIELD OF 2 MR/HR. OR GREATER. ACTIONS TAKEN BY FIRST RESPONDERS WOULD PROBABLY HAVE BEEN NO DIFFERENT HAD SOPHISTICATED INSTRUMENTATION BEEN AVAILABLE AT THE SCENE FOR DETAILED ASSESSMENT.

column168: PRODUCT ODOR WAS REPORTED EMANATING FROM UTLX 38448 AND THIS TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  THE BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER INVESTIGATING THE SOURCE OF PRODUCT ODOR REPORTED FROST AROUND THE THEROMETER WELL CAP.  RESPONDER ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE THEROMETER WELL CAP BUT THE SLIGHT RELEASE CONTINUED.  AS THIS WAS A LOW PRESSURE RELEASE, THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP WAS REMOVED AND TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO THE THREADED AREAS AND THE CAP WAS REAPPLIED.  THE SLIGHT LEAK CONTINUED.  THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP WAS AGAIN REMOVED AND A WOODEN PLUG WITH SEALANT WAS INSERTED INTO THE PIPING ORIFICE.  AN O-RING WAS INSERTED INTO THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP AND THE CAP WAS REAPPLIED AND TOOL TIGHTENED, ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE ON 12/17/05.  FRA-05120328 MOVEMENT APPROVAL WAS RECEIVED TO TRANSPORT UTLX 38448 BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR PRODUCT UNLOADING.  SHIPPER TO ARRANGE TO SEND UTLX 38448 TO A REPAIR FACILITY AFTER TANK CAR IS UNLOADED.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED CGTX 30107 IN RAILYARD DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) AREA.  CGTX 30107 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED TO THE LOCOMOTIVE FUELING PAD TRACKS THAT HAVE TRACK PANEL DRIP CATCH SYSTEMS IN PLACE.  BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDER INSPECTED CGTX 30107 AND AT THAT TIME FOUND NO PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOV, BUT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE CAP (BOC) REVEALED FRESH PRODUCT STAINS.  THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOV WAS CLOSED, SEALED AND THE OPERATIN GHANDLE WAS PINNED.  THE BOC WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  WITH A BUCKET UNDER THE BOV, THE RESPONDER REMOVED THE BOC FOR INSPECTION OF THE BOC GASKET WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION AND POSITION.  THE BOC WAS REAPPLIED AND PROPERLY TOOL TIGTHENED ENDING ANY FURTHER PRODUCT DRIPS BY NOON 12/18/05.  ALL SPILLAGE APPEARED TO BE EVAPORATING.  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR INSPECTED SPILL AREA FOR GROUND IMPACT AND REMEDIATED ANY NON-EVAPORATED GROUND SPILLAGE.

column168: GATX 90917 AT REPAIR TRACK FOR AIR BRAKE WORK IN RAILYARD WAS REPORTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV). BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER REPORTED PRODUCT WAS OOZING FROM THE BOV BOTTOM OPERATING HANDLE AND WHERE THE 4 INCH BALL VALVE BOV WAS BOLTED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  THE FLANGE BOLTS APPEARED TO BE TOOL TIGHT AND COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED FURTHER.  A CRACK WAS ALSO NOTICED IN THE AUXILIARY PIPING THAT WAS WELDED TO THE PRIMARY BOV ASSEMBLY.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR, GATX 300749, TO BE SENT TO BARSTOW FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER.  PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED ON 12/22/05 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  APPROXIMATELY 9 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS CAPTURED IN RECEPTACLES PLACED UNDER GATX 90917.  FRA MOVEMENT ARRPOVAL FRA-05120329 WAS RECEIVED TO FORWARD GATX 90917 TO THE DESIGNATED REPAIR FACILITY AT COLTON, CA.

column168: APA RR REJECTED ACFX 94332 AT INTERCHANGE DUE TO DRIED PRODUCT RESIDUE ON ITS TANK SHELL. BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS CHECKED THE PRODUCT OUTAGE IN ACFX 94332 AND IT MEASURED 10 INCHES OF OUTAGE, THEREFORE ACFX 94332 WAS NOT OVERFILLED.  HYDRAULIC PRESSURE SURGES MOST LIKELY CAUSED THE PRV TO EXPEL LIQUID PRODUCT.  THE BNSF CONTRACTOR ALSO NEUTRALIZED AND WIPED ALL PRODUCT SPILLAGE ON THE TANK SHELL OF ACFX 94332 ON 12/14/05.  AFTERWARDS, ACFX 94332 WAS INTERCHANGED TO THE APA RR.

column168: Approximately 2:00 PM:    As the roll-off box was being transported to PSC-Tacoma, the driver noticed smoke coming out of one of the two roll off boxes he had on his truck. The driver pulled over to the side of the road and called the facility for further instructions. PSC employees called 911 and checked the waste profile and informed the dispatcher and transportation group that there may be batteries in the box and to use fire fighting foam to fight the fire.     Approximately 2:02 PM:   The driver pulled into the facility a couple of minutes later, and the rear roll off box had smoke coming out of it. Employees got the facility's foam cannon set up while the box was moved onto the west pad (into secondary containment) to be able to contain any potential run off or overflow.     Approximately 2:20 PM:  The driver opened up the lid of the box just as the fire department showed up. When the air hit the material in the box the fire flared up, PSC employees turned on the foam cannon and began the fire suppression. The fire department then came over and took over the operation of the foam cannon. The cannon was moved a little closer to the box for better coverage, and after several minutes the fire was put out.     Approximately 2:50PM:  The fire department continued shooting foam into the roll off until it was full. They then informed PSC to wait to drain the box to ensure everything was out and the material had cooled down. After the fire was out and the box had been filled with foam.    Approximately 3:15 PM:  Deputy Fire Marshal Lee Britt, stated that he was going to report this as a dumpster fire and thanked PSC for good decision-making and assistance.
column169: The following background information was provided by a representative from the generator of the roll-off box in question, Mercer Distribution Services (a warehouse and distribution company located in Auburn, Washington):    -In August 2005, Mercer had a fire at their facility that was believed to have been caused by nickel-cadmium batteries that came into contact with various building materials while being offloaded from a transport trailer.    -Mercer contracted with Western States Environmental to provide cleanup services following the fire, and they placed the cleanup debris into the roll-off box in question.  The generator thought it was possible that the contractor may have placed live nickel-cadmium batteries into the box containing the cleanup debris.      After the roll-off box fire had been completely extinguished, PSC personnel inspected the contents of the box and noticed that several batteries were commingled with debris in the location where the fire appeared to have started.      A second roll-off box was also included in the shipment, but it was not involved in the fire.  The contents of this box were inspected, but no batteries could be seen.  The box appears to contain only charred building materials from the cleanup of the August fire, matching PSC’s approved waste profile for the shipment.    As PSC was acting only as the transporter at the time of the incident, we have communicated our concerns to the generator regarding this incident.  Specifically, the generator has been advised that materials placed into roll-off boxes must be carefully sorted to insure incompatible or non-conforming materials are not commingled.

column168: At approximately 1515 hours on 12-27-05, Apria employee Tracey Brodd was involved in a single vehicle accident on a rural road (dirt) 2 miles south and .5 mile east of Jennings, KS. Brodd was driving an Apria 2001 Isuzu, FRR, box truck, NE license 48-1246. He was traveling east bound at approximately 25 MPH and when he tried to maneuver the truck to the center of the roadway as he approached a one lane wide bridge he lost control of the vehicle in the mud. The truck impacted the side of the bridge at approximately the middle, road side of the vehicle at the side door.    The impact caved in the side of the vehicle at the side, roll up, door and intruded into the cargo area. The impact severed the plumbing and control valves on the fill/discharge line. As a result of the plumbing being severed from the non-specification cargo tank approximately 150 liquid gallons of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid was released onto the ground.    Brodd contacted his office, McCook, NE. via radio and they contacted the Decatur County (KS) Sheriffs Office.    Upon the responding officers arrival it was found that the cargo tank had emptied and the spill had vaporized and dissipated. The vehicle was released by the responding officer and towed from the scene.    Brodd was uninjured and there was no collateral damage.

THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TILFORD YARD IN ATLANTA, GA, ADVISED THAT A YARD CREW REPORTED A STRONG SULFUR ODOR IN CLASS YARD TRACK 23.  THERE WERE 4 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARS IN TRACK 23 INCLUDING A GATX 17106, RESIDUE SULFUR DIOXIDE AND ECUX 259093, LOAD MOLTEN SULFUR.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CARS IN TRACK 23 FOR POSSIBLE LEAKAGE.  THEY FOUND THAT THE GATX 17106 HAD ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS SECURE AND THERE WAS NO SIGN OF ANY LEAKAGE FROM IT.  THE ODOR APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM THE ECUX 259093.  THEY FOUND THAT ALL OF THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  THEY TIGHTENED THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS AND THE ODOR DISSIPATED.  THE SHIPPER, EXXONMOBIL CHEMICAL WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC (REPORT # 12092005033.)  EXXONMOBIL WAS ADVISED OF THE SOURCE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: CONWAY DOCKWORKER MORRISON WAS STRIPPING TRAILER 415-3281.  HE FOUND A SKID OF PAINT FLIPPED OVER IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, THE SKID HAD BEEN STACKED ON TOP OF SOME DRUMS, BUT IT HAD NOT BEEN BLOCKED IN.  THERE WAS PAINT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  ONE PAIL WAS UPSIDE-DOWN AND SEEPING PAINT FROM THE LID.  THE PAIL WAS TURNED OVER AND THE LID WAS RESEALED.  THAT PAIL WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION.  ANOTHER PAIL WAS FOUND LAYING ON ITS SIDE WITH A KINK IN THE SIDE.  WHEN MORRISON PUT THE PAIL UPRIGHT IT STARTED TO LEAK FROM THE CRACK IN THE SIDE.  HE THEN PUT THAT PAIL INTO A SALVAGE DRUM, AND PLACED IT IN OUR HAZMAT OSD.
column169: THE DRIVER WHO LOADED THIS FREIGHT SHOULD HAVE BLOCKED AND BRACED IT IN THE TRAILER.  THAT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: XME DSR LAWRENCE SPARKS WAS LOADING FREIGHT (A SMALL SKID).  THE FORKS WERE STICKING OUT BEYOND THE SKID AT LEAST A FOOT.  HE WAS LOADING THE SKID BEHIND THE PAINT AND HIS FORK PUNCTURED THE PAIL, CAUSING THE LEAK.
column169: BE MINDFUL OF YOUR FORKS STICKING OUT BEYOND THE SKID WHEN LOADING FREIGHT
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column169: TO PREVENT IN THE FUTURE, SKIDS SHOULD BE CHECKED TO MAKE SURE NAILS AREN'T STICKING UP.  ALSO, BETTER SHRINK WRAPPING WOULD LIKELY PREVENT SHIFTING OF FREIGHT ON SKID.

column168: AT 4:45 JUSTIN ANDERSON RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE.  HE PUT HIS PPE GEAR ON AND RESPONDED PROPERLY.  HE FOUND THE PACKAGE INSIDE THE TRAILER ON TOP OF FLAPS.  THEN WE(CHET FERRARI AND JUSTIN) CLEANED THE SPILL USING OUR DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.

ON DECEMBER 22, 2005 WE RECEIVED AN EMAIL FROM ONE OF OUR TERMINAL MANAGERS STATING THAT PERSONNEL FROM NUCOR YAMATO WERE HEADING TO THE SCENE OF A SPILL OF K061 FLUE DUST ON HIGHWAY 18 LEADING TO BLYTHEVILLE, AR.  THE SPILL WAS ALLEGEDLY FROM ONE OF OUR FIVE TRUCKS LOADING AT NUCOR YAMATO WHICH IS WHY WE WERE CONTACTED.  WE CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AS REQUIRED TO REPORT WHAT WE KNEW AT THE TIME AND TALKED TO KEVIN WILLIAMS (REPORT # 783185).  AFTER NUCOR YAMATO PERSONNEL INVESTIGATED THE SITE OF THE ALLEGED SPILL, THEY RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY A POUND OF K061, WHICH IS NOT AN RQ FOR K061 AND DOES NOT COMPEL US TO CONTACT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  UPON CALLING ERIC DELGADO AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, WE WERE TOLD THAT THE REPORT COULD NOT BE CANCELLED AND FORM DOT F 5800.1 NEEDED TO BE COMPLETED AND SENT IN.  THEREFORE, THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED AS A "PROTECTIVE REPORT" ONLY.  WE WERE IN CONTACT WITH TOM HUNTING, ADQ HAZWASTE DIVISION WHO STATED THAT NO FURTHER ACTION IS ANTICIPATED.  RICHARD MERRITT, ADQ EMERGENCY RESPONSE STATED THAT "FROM WHAT I HEAR I GUESS IT'S ALL UNDER CONTROL."  THE FIVE TRUCKS INVOLVED IN THE TRANSPORTATION OF THE MATERAIL THAT DAY WERE INSPECTED AT TRUCK FACILITIES FOR LEAKS AND FOUND TO HAVE NONE.  IT HAS STILL NOT BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS FROM ONE OF OUR TRUCKS.

column168: SKP DRIVER, ELLIOT CLARK, STATED THAT HE SWERVED TO MISS A DOG, WHICH RESULTED IN THE FAILURE OF THE LEFT FRONT TIRE. THE FAILURE OF THE TIRE CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (UNIT #838 - T-925) TO FLIP ON TO IT'S SIDE, TURN 180 DEGREE INTO ONCOMING TRAFFIC, AND SLIDE INTO THE GUARDRAIL. THIS INCIDENT RELEASED THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE WESTERN FORESLOPE OF SOUTH BOUND I-40 AT ABOUT MILE MARKER 432 BETWEEN EXIT 432 AND SINKING CREEK.   THE ACCIDENT WAS A ONE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  THE SPILL RESULTED IN CLOSING A LANE OF I-40 E, APPROXIMATELY, 1/4 MILE, FOR A PERIOD OF APPROXIMATELY 8 HOURS.
column169: AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT, SKP HAS DISPERSED A MEMO TO ITS DRIVER REMINDING THEM TO BE UNDER CONTROL ALWAYS, AND TO USE DISCRETION WHEN ANIMAL LIFE IS IN JEOPARDY.

column168: THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER THE PACKAGE BUT WAS UNABLE TO BECAUSE THE SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE WAS INCORRECT.  SHANTELLE OBST OPENED THE PACKAGE TO LOOK FOR AN INVOICE THAT CONTAINED TO SHIPPER INFORMATION.  SHE DISCOVER THE FIREWORKS AND TURNED THE PACKAGE OVER TO ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR.  THE SORT WAS UNABLE TO CORRECT THE ADDRESS AND SUBMITTED A HARD COPY OF PAPERWORK.

SHIPMENT WAS OPENED FOR INSPECTION BY ODC CLERK BECAUSE THE INVOICE LISTED THE CONTENTS VAGUELY AS "NMB HARDWARE" AND "SHK 250." UPON INSPECTION, THE CLERK DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKAGE CONTENTS INCLUDED TWO AEROSOL CANS OF SPRAY PAINT.  THESE TWO CANS WERE MARKED "CONSUMER COMMODITY" AND ORM-D."  THERE WERE NO OUTER PACKAGE MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS, NOR DID THE INVOICE LIST THE CONTENTS AS EITHER HAZARDOUS OR AS 'AEROSOL CANS,' SPRAY PAINT', ETC.  A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION/HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS WERE NOT PRESENT.  THE HELPINE WAS CONSULTED (KELLY @ 19:28) AND BASED ON THEIR ADVICE, THE SHIPMENT WAS TREATED ASN UNDECLARED HAZMAT.
column169: THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO CORRECTLY DOCUMENT, MARK, AND LABEL ANY AIR SHIPMENT CONTAINING "CONSUMER COMMODITIES."

column168: THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY HUMAN ERROR.  OUR EQUIPMENT DID NOT FAIL NOR DID THE TANK AT THE UNIVERSITY WHERE WE UNLOADED FAIL.  PETROLEUM TRADERS CALLED OUR ST. LOUIS, MO TERMIANL TO ORDER A LOAD TO THE UNIVERSITY GAS STATION.  OUR ST. LOUIS DRIVER DELIVERED TO THE UNIVERSITY AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM ON 12/27/05.  PETROLEUM TRADERS ALSO CALLED OUR JEFFERSON CITY, MO TRAILER TO REQUEST A LOAD TO BE DELIVERED TO THE UNIVERSITY GAS STATION.  OUR DISPATCHERS AND DRIVER FOLLOWED THE INSTRUCTIONS GIVEN TO THEM.  OUR JEFFERSON CITY, MO DISPATCHER FOLLOWED THE INSTRUCTIONS THE UNIVERSITY HAD GIVEN.  SHE CALLED THE UNIVERSITY TO TELL THEM OUR DRIVER WAS LOADED AND ON HIS WAY.  OUR DRIVERS DO NOT HAVE ACCESS TO THE REMOTE TANK GAUGE READOUT.  THERE IS NO EXTERNAL GAUGE ON THE TANK THAT THE DRIVER COULD READ TO KNOW THAT THE TANK WAS NEARLY FULL.  UNIVERSITY PERSONNEL WAS TO OPEN THE GATE, TAKE THE TANK READING AND RETURN TO GET THE BOL AND LOCK GATE.  WHEN OUR SECOND DRIVER ARRIVED THE GATE WAS WIDE OPEN WHICH INDICATED SOMEONE HAD READ THE TANK GAUGES AND IT WAS OKAY TO UNLOAD.  THERE ARE TWO TANKS SURROUNDING BY A CHAINLINK FENCE WITH A MAN GATE.  THE TANK IS SITTING INSIDE A RECTANGULAR METAL BOX.  THERE IS A METAL SHIELD WELDED TO THE BOX.  GASOLINE SPRAYED FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK ONTO THE METAL SHIELD AND DEFLECTED INTO THE TANK CONTAINMENT BOX.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALS. WENT ON THE GRAVEL AND 15-20 GALLONS IN THE METAL CONTAINMENT BOX.  THE UNIVERSITY AND PETROLEUM TRADERS HAVE HANDLED THE CLEANUP.  MISSOURI EPA (ALAN CORTVRIENT) SPOKE WITH MIKE AKERS, GENERAL MANAGER AT THE UNIVERSITY, AND WAS SATISFIED WITH THE SITUATION.
column169: PETROLEUM TRADERS SHOULD BRING THIS PROBLEM OF DOUBLE-DISPATCHING TO THEIR EMPLOYEE'S ATTENTION AND REVIEW PROCEUDRES.  IN THE PAST A UNIVERSITY EMPLOYEE WOULD OPEN THE GATE, TAKE THE TANK READING, AND LEAVE THE GATE OPEN.  THE GATE BEING OPEN INDICATED SOMEONE HAD READ THE GAUGES AND IT WAS OKAY TO UNLOAD.  WHEN OUR DRIVER WAS FINISHED HE WAS TO CLOSE THE GATE.  THEY WOULD RETURN AND GET THE BILL OF LADING AND LOCK THE GATE.  OUR DRIVER HAD FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS WHEN HE MADE PREVIOUS DELIVERIES.  MOST OF TIME A UNIVERSITY EMPLOYEE WOULD UNLOCK HAND WHEEL ON THE VALVE AND THE DRIVER WAS TO CLOOSE VALVE AND LOCK PADLOCK.  NEW INSTRUCTION BY THE UNIVERSITY GAS STATION:  DO NOT PUMP UNTIL AN EMPLOYEE COMES AND TELLS DRIVER IT IS OKAY TO UNLOAD.

column168: ON 12/28/05 A DRIVER FOLLOWING OUR TRUCK NOTICED SOMETHING DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER AND CALLED 911. THE TRUCK WAS PULLED OVER THE LOUISIANA HIGHWAY PATROL. THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK CALLED ALLEN PAQUETTE, OWNER OF THE TRUCK THAT HE HAD A SPILL COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER, WHICH THE DRIVER CONTAINED WITH DIRT.    ALLEN PAQUETTE CALLED JONES ENVIRONMENTAL IN BOSSIER CITY, LA TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 5:00PM A PHONE CALL FROM THE DRIVER THAT A SERGEANT BOBBIT WAS ON THE SCENE, ALONG WITH THE FIRE DEPT AND HAZMAT TEAM FROM MONROE, LA. APPROXIMATELY 5:30PM I HAD SIGNED A CONTRACT WITH JONES ENVIRONMENTAL AND FAXED IT BACK TO THEM. THEY SAID THEY WERE RESPONDING. AT 7:00PM JONES ENVIRONMENTAL CALLED AND SAID THAT THEY NEEDED $27,000.00 DEPOSIT BEFORE THEY COULD DISPATCH THEIR TEAM. AT 7:30PM U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. SEE ATTACHED INFORMATION FROM UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, LLC.

column168: ON TUESDAY, DECEMBER 20, 2005, COMBUSTIN ENGINEERING, INC. (THE SHIPPER) LOCATED AT 2000 DAY HILL ROAD IN WINDSOR, CONNECTICUT WAS NOTIFIED BY ITS DECOMMISSIONING PROJECT CONTRACTOR, MACTEC, OF AN INCIDENT RELATED TO THE TRANSPORT OF RADIOACTIVE WASTE FROM THE WINDSOR, CT FACILITY TO ENVIROCARE OF UTAH. THE WASTE TRANSPORTATION LOGISTICS CONTRACTOR, CAVANAGH SERVICES GROUP (CSG), NOTIFIED  MACTEC OF THE INCIDENT. CSG WAS USING TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT(TSMT) AS THE CARRIER FOR THIS SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF FIVE 96-CU FT. (B-25) CONTAINERS. TWO OF THE PACKAGES WERE MARKED AND PLACARDED AS CLASS 7 LSA RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL. THE REMAINING THREE PACKAGES WERE MARKED AS LIMITED QUANTITY RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL. THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER PURSUANT TO FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER FILED CASE NUMBER 783-009 REGARDING THIS INCIDENT.   INCIDENT:    ON MONDAY, DECEMBER 19,2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:25PM CENTRAL TIME, THE TSMT SAFETY OFFICE RECEIVED A VERBAL NOTIFICATION FROM THE TSMT DRIVER THAT SHIPMENT NUMBER CEMAC-2005-19 (0923-01-0045), TRACTOR NUMBER 43046, TRAILER NUMBER 848144, HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A MOVING VEHICLE ACCIDENT ON INTERSTATE 80 WESTBOUND NEAR RAWLINS, WYOMING NEAR MILEMARKER 213. REPORTS FROM TSMT INDICATED THAT A LATE MODEL PICKUP TRUCK SPUN OUT OF CONTROL STRIKING THE GUARDRAIL ON THE LEFT LANE OF THE HIGHWAY (FIGURE 1). AFTER COLLIDING WITH THE GUARDRAIL, THE PICKUP ROLLED INTO THE TSMT TRUCK'S LANE OF TRAVEL RESULTING IN A COLLISION. THE COLLISION CAUSED THE DAMAGE TO THE TRUCK THAT RESULTED IN A LOSS OF STEERING. THE TSMT VEHICLE VEERED OFF THE ROAD AND WENT DOWN THE EMBANKMENT ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY (FIGURE 2). THE TRACTOR AND FLATBED TRAILER REMAINED IN AN UPRIGHT ORIENTATION DURING AND FOLLOWING THE COLLISION. THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL PACKAGES REMAINED UPRIGHT ON THE TRAILER AND REMAINED SEALED. NO RELEASE OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL OCCURRED FROM THE SHIPMENT DURING THE ACCIDENT. PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHMENT FOR A COPY OF THE WY STATE POLICE REPORT.   THE TSMT DRIVER CONTACTED THE TSMT SAFETY OFFICE IN ACCORDANCE WITH TSMT PROCEDURES. THE TSMT SAFETY OFFICE CONTACTED THE TSMT EXTENDED OPERATIONS COVERAGE. TSMT SAFETY PERSONNEL CONTACTED THE POLICE AND EMERGENCY RESPONDERS FROM THE RAWLINS, WY FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE TSMT DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED DURING THE ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER OF THE PICKUP TRUCK SUSTAINED NON-LIFE THREATENING INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT ACCORDING TO REPORTS FROM THE RESPONDING STATE HIGHWAY PATROL OFFICER. THE POLICE OFFICER INFORMED THE TSMT DRIVER THAT THE PICKUP TRUCK DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL VIA AMBULANCE.  THE TSMT DRIVER AND EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND THE SHIPMENT. THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS PERFORMED RADIOLOGICAL SURVEYS ON THE TRAILER ON THE TRAILER AND AT THE ACCIDENT SITE WITH RADIATION DETECTION KITS. NO EVIDENCE WAS FOUND INDICATING THAT THE CONTAINERS WERE COMPROMISED BECAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT. INSPECTION OF THE
column169: THE ACCIDENT WAS NOT THE FAULT OF THE TSMT DRIVER AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS NOT RELEASED FROM THE SHIPMENT. THEREFORE, NO VIOLATION OCCURRED.

column168: KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED BULKTAINER ILIU 1830101 WAS RELEASING ITS PORUDCT AT A RATE OF ONE CUP PER HOUR WHILE LOCATED IN THE BAILEY YARD IN NORTH PLATTE, NE. MR. KEELING ADVISED THE PORUDCT WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE JACKET OF THE TANK.  MR. KEELING FURTHER ADVISED THERE WERE NO INJURIES, EXPOSURES, OR EVACUATIONS AS A RESULT OF THE INDICENT.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.    AT 05:27 PM, ROBERT MORRISON, SENION SPECIAL AGENT, ADVISED THE BULTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE EAST END OF THE YARD.  AT 05:57 PM, KEELING ADVISED TWO GALLONS OF THE ORUDCT HAD BEEN CAPTURED IN A CONTAINER AND STARTED THE MATERIAL WHICH TOUCHED THE GORUND HAD EVAPORATED.    AT 09:07 PM, KEELING ADVISED THE SHIPPER COULD STILL NOT BE REACHED AND REQUESTED CHEMTREC BE CONTACTED FOR ADDTIONAL SHIPPER INFORMATION.  AT 11:16 PM, MR. KEELING ADVISED THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.  MR. KEELING FURTHER STATED COORDINATIONWITH THE SHIPPER FOR TRANSLOADING THE REMAINING PORUDCT WAS ONGOING AND MORE INFOMRATION WOULD BE AVAILABLE AFTER DAYLIGHT HOURS.    ON 12/22/05M AT 01:l11 AM, KEELING ADVISED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A TEN INCH FRACTURE IN THE WELD OF THE HEAD OF THE TANK.  THE FRACTURE RAN THE LENGTH OF THE WLED INTERSECTING THE TANK SUPPORT ON THE RIGHT SIDE BOTTOM END OF THE TANK.  THE LAK WAS TEMPORARILY  SECURED WITH A FRACTURE SEALIER AND THEN THE FRACTURE WAS SECURED WITH THREE STEEL STICK EXPOXY'S.  THE SUPPORTS FOR THE TANK HAD BEEN REPOARED PREVIOUSLY WITH A LIGHT GAUGE METAL STRIP AND AN ATTEMPT HAD BEEN MADE BY SOMEONE PREVIOUSLY TO STOP THE LEAK BY PALCING SILICONE ON A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE JACKET.  WHEN THE JACKET FILLED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET THE OPRDUCT RAN OUT A SEAM IN THE JACKET, THIS IS WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED BY TRACK INSPECTOR HEATH DENISE.  THE FIVE PACK THIS BULKTAINER WAS ON WAS RELEASED TO JOHN ROLAND, CAR DEPARTMENT MANAGER, AT 11:30 PM WHERE IT COULD BE PLACED BACK IN TRANSPORTATION.    PM 12/23/05 AT 04:59 AM, RON EDELL, SENIOR MANAGEROF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, ADVISED THE BULTAINER WAS GROUNDED IN THE VAN YARD AND WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR, KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIROMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT MR. EDELL, AT 05:42 AM, KEELING ADVISED HAZMAT RESPONPSE WAS EN ROUTE TO INVESTIGATE.  AT 05:58 AM, KEELING ADVISED THE ODOR APPEARED TO BE RESIDUAL FROM THE EARLIER RELEASE, 01/03/2006 ALL PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED AND THE BULTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM UPRR PROPERTY.  THE WASTE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS PORDUCT WILL BE HANDLED THROUGH HAZ-MAT RESPONSE INC. AND ITT THE SHIPPER.
